question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected
answer_EN: The CIA's headquarters is located in Langley , McLean , Fairfax County, Virginia , a few miles west of Washington, D.C..

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected
answer_EN: The CIA succeeded the Office of Strategic Services (OSS), formed during World War II to coordinate secret espionage activities against the Axis Powers for the branches of the United States Armed Forces .
answer: CIA는 제2차 세계대전 당시 미군 지부를 위해 추축국에 대한 비밀 첩보 활동을 조정하기 위해 설립된 전략 서비스국(OSS)을 계승한 기관입니다.

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

answer: 1947년 국가보안법에 따라 CIA는 "국내외에서 경찰이나 법 집행 기능을 수행할 수 없다"는 조항을 두고 설립되었습니다.

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

answer: CIA의 주요 기능은 외국 정부, 기업 및 개인에 대한 정보를 수집하고 공공 정책 입안자에게 조언하는 것이지만 긴급 전술 작전을 수행하고 비밀 작전을 수행하며 특수 활동 부서와 같은 전술 부서를 통해 외국 정치에 영향력을 행사합니다.

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

answer: 보안 및 방첩 실패, 정보 분석 실패, 인권 문제, 외부 조사 및 문서 공개, 여론 및 법 집행에 대한 영향력 행사, 마약 밀매, 의회 거짓말 등과 관련하여 CIA에 대한 상당한 비판이 있어 왔습니다.

question_EN: how is cia headquarters protected

question_EN: how far is a league

answer: 해상 거리의 경우, 3마일(4.8km) 거리는 평균 신장(5'9" 또는 1.78m)의 관찰자가 해수면에 서 있을 때 볼 수 있는 거리에 해당합니다.

question_EN: how far is a league

question_EN: what can sql 2005 do

question_EN: what can sql 2005 do

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: what does google don't be evil mean?

question_EN: What band will at&t 4g network be on?

question_EN: What band will at&t 4g network be on?

question_EN: What band will at&t 4g network be on?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?
answer_EN: Sperm donation is the provision (or ‘donation’) by a man, (known as a ‘sperm donor’), of his sperm , with the intention that it be used to impregnate a woman who is not his sexual partner.

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

answer: 정자 기증자는 자신의 기증으로 인해 태어난 모든 자녀의 자연적 또는 생물학적 아버지가 되지만, 일반적으로 법적 또는 법적인 아버지가 되지는 않습니다.

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how much does a man make for donating sperm?

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: A diplexer is a passive device that implements frequency domain multiplexing .
answer: 다이플렉서는 주파수 도메인 멀티플렉싱을 구현하는 수동 장치입니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: Two ports (e.g., L and H) are multiplexed onto a third port (e.g., S).
answer: 두 개의 포트(예: L 및 H)가 세 번째 포트(예: S)에 멀티플렉싱됩니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: The signals on ports L and H occupy disjoint frequency bands.
answer: 포트 L과 H의 신호는 서로 다른 주파수 대역을 사용합니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: Consequently, the signals on L and H can coexist on port S without interfering with each other.
answer: 따라서 L과 H의 신호는 서로 간섭하지 않고 포트 S에서 공존할 수 있습니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: In that situation, the diplexer consists of a lowpass filter connecting ports L and S and high pass filter connecting ports H and S. Ideally, all the signal power on port L is transferred to the S port and vice versa.
answer: 이 상황에서 다이플렉서는 포트 L과 S를 연결하는 저역 통과 필터와 포트 H와 S를 연결하는 고역 통과 필터로 구성되며, 이상적으로는 포트 L의 모든 신호 전력이 S 포트로 전송되고 그 반대의 경우도 마찬가지입니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: All the signal power on port H is transferred to port S and vice versa.
answer: 포트 H의 모든 신호 전원은 포트 S로 전송되며, 그 반대의 경우도 마찬가지입니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: The diplexer, being a passive device, is reciprocal: the device itself doesn't have a notion of input or output.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: There is also a power "loss" difference - a combiner takes all the power delivered to the S port and equally divides it between the A and B ports.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: A diplexer does not.
answer: 다이플렉서는 그렇지 않습니다.

question_EN: how does a triplexer work?
answer_EN: A diplexer multiplexes two ports onto one port, but more than two ports may be multiplexed: a three-port to one-port multiplexer is known as a triplexer.

answer_EN: Baptism of Neophytes by Masaccio , 15th century, Brancacci Chapel , Florence .

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Baptism (from the Greek noun βάπτισμα baptisma; itself derived from βαπτισμός baptismos, washing) is a Christian rite of admission (or adoption ), almost invariably with the use of water, into the Christian Church generally and also a particular church tradition.
answer: 세례(그리스 명사 βάπτισμα baptisma에서 유래, 그 자체는 βαπτισμός baptismos, 씻음에서 유래)는 거의 항상 물을 사용하여 기독교 교회에 일반적으로 그리고 특정 교회 전통에 입교(또는 입양 )하는 기독교 의례입니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Baptism has been called a sacrament and an ordinance of Jesus Christ.
answer: 세례는 예수 그리스도의 성례전이자 의식이라고 불립니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: In some traditions, baptism is also called christening, but for others the word "christening" is reserved for the baptism of infants .
answer: 일부 전통에서는 세례를 세례라고도하지만 다른 전통에서는 "세례"라는 단어가 유아 세례 를 위해 예약되어 있습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: The New Testament reports that Jesus was baptized .
answer: 신약 성경에는 예수님이 세례를 받으셨다고 기록되어 있습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: The usual form of baptism among the earliest Christians was for the naked candidate to be immersed totally (submersion) or partially (standing or kneeling in water while water was poured on him or her).
answer: 초기 기독교인들의 일반적인 세례 형태는 벌거벗은 지원자가 물에 완전히 잠기거나(침수) 부분적으로(서 있거나 무릎을 꿇고 물을 붓는 동안) 물에 잠기는 것이었습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: While John the Baptist 's use of a deep river for his baptism suggests immersion, pictorial and archaeological evidence of Christian baptism from the 3rd century onward indicates that a normal form was to have the candidate stand in water while water was poured over the upper body.
answer: 세례 요한이 세례를 받을 때 깊은 강물을 사용한 것은 침수를 암시하지만, 3세기 이후 기독교 세례의 그림과 고고학적 증거에 따르면 상체에 물을 붓는 동안 후보자가 물속에 서 있는 것이 일반적인 형태였음을 알 수 있습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Other common forms of baptism now in use include pouring water three times on the forehead.
answer: 현재 사용되고 있는 다른 일반적인 세례 형태로는 이마에 물을 세 번 붓는 것이 있습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Martyrdom was identified early in Church history as "baptism by blood", enabling martyrs who had not been baptized by water to be saved.
answer: 순교는 교회 역사 초기에 '피에 의한 세례'로 인식되어 물로 세례를 받지 않은 순교자들도 구원을 받을 수 있었습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Later, the Catholic Church identified a baptism of desire , by which those preparing for baptism who die before actually receiving the sacrament are considered saved.
answer: 나중에 가톨릭 교회는 실제로 성찬을 받기 전에 사망한 세례 준비자가 구원받은 것으로 간주하는 소망의 세례 를 확인했습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: As evidenced also in the common Christian practice of infant baptism , baptism was universally seen by Christians as in some sense necessary for salvation , until Huldrych Zwingli in the 16th century denied its necessity.
answer: 유아 세례의 일반적인 기독교 관습에서도 알 수 있듯이, 16세기 훌드리히 츠빙글리가 세례의 필요성을 부정하기 전까지 세례는 어떤 의미에서 구원을 위해 필요한 것으로 기독교인들에게 보편적으로 여겨졌습니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Among those that do, differences can be found in the manner and mode of baptizing and in the understanding of the significance of the rite.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from
answer_EN: Most Christians baptize "in the name of the Father , and of the Son , and of the Holy Spirit " (following the Great Commission ), but some baptize in Jesus' name only .
answer: 대부분의 기독교인은 "성부와 성자와 성령의 이름으로"(지상 명령에 따라) 세례를 받지만, 일부는 예수의 이름으로만 세례를 받기도 합니다.

question_EN: Where does the word baptism come from

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: heritability of a trait within a population is the proportion of observable differences in a trait between individuals within a population that is due to genetic differences.
answer: 집단 내 형질의 유전성은 유전적 차이로 인한 집단 내 개체 간 형질의 관찰 가능한 차이의 비율을 의미합니다.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Factors including genetics , environment and random chance can all contribute to the variation between individuals in their observable characteristics (in their " phenotypes ").

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Heritability thus analyzes the relative contributions of differences in genetic and non-genetic factors to the total phenotypic variance in a population.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: For instance, some humans in a population are taller than others; heritability attempts to identify how much genetics are playing a role in part of the population being extra tall.
answer: 예를 들어, 인구 중 일부가 다른 사람보다 키가 큰 경우 유전성은 인구의 일부가 키가 큰 데 유전이 어느 정도 영향을 미치는지 파악하려고 시도합니다.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Heritability is an important concept in quantitative genetics , particularly in selective breeding and behaviour genetics (for instance twin studies ), but is less widely used in population genetics .
answer: 유전성은 양적 유전학, 특히 선택적 육종 및 행동 유전학(예: 쌍둥이 연구)에서 중요한 개념이지만 인구 유전학에서는 널리 사용되지 않습니다.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Heritability measures the fraction of phenotype variability that can be attributed to genetic variation.
answer: 유전성은 유전적 변이에 기인할 수 있는 표현형 변동성의 비율을 측정합니다.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: This is not the same as saying that this fraction of an individual phenotype is caused by genetics.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: In addition, heritability can change without any genetic change occurring (e.g. when the environment starts contributing to more variation).

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: On the other hand, heritability might also increase if the environmental variation decreases, causing individuals to show less phenotypic variation (e.g. to show more similar levels of intelligence).

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Heritability is increasing because genetics are contributing more variation, or because non-genetic factors are contributing less variation; what matters is the relative contribution.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Here we see why heritability is specific to a particular population in a particular environment.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: The extent of dependence of phenotype on environment can also be a function of the genes involved.

question_EN: WHAT ARE HERITABLE TRAITS
answer_EN: Matters of heritability are complicated because genes may canalize a phenotype, making its expression almost inevitable in all occurring environments.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: The technique is used to improve storage utilization and can also be applied to network data transfers to reduce the number of bytes that must be sent.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: In the deduplication process, unique chunks of data, or byte patterns, are identified and stored during a process of analysis.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: As the analysis continues, other chunks are compared to the stored copy and whenever a match occurs, the redundant chunk is replaced with a small reference that points to the stored chunk.
answer: 분석이 계속되면 다른 청크가 저장된 사본과 비교되고 일치하는 항목이 발생할 때마다 중복 청크는 저장된 청크를 가리키는 작은 참조로 대체됩니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: Given that the same byte pattern may occur dozens, hundreds, or even thousands of times (the match frequency is dependent on the chunk size), the amount of data that must be stored or transferred can be greatly reduced.
answer: 동일한 바이트 패턴이 수십, 수백, 수천 번 발생할 수 있으므로(일치 빈도는 청크 크기에 따라 달라짐) 저장하거나 전송해야 하는 데이터의 양을 크게 줄일 수 있습니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: This type of deduplication is different from that performed by standard file-compression tools, such as LZ77 and LZ78 .
answer: 이러한 유형의 중복 제거는 LZ77 및 LZ78 과 같은 표준 파일 압축 도구에서 수행하는 중복 제거와는 다릅니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: Whereas these tools identify short repeated substrings inside individual files, the intent of storage-based data deduplication is to inspect large volumes of data and identify large sections – such as entire files or large sections of files – that are identical, in order to store only one copy of it.
answer: 이러한 도구는 개별 파일 내에서 짧게 반복되는 하위 문자열을 식별하는 반면, 스토리지 기반 데이터 중복 제거의 목적은 대량의 데이터를 검사하고 전체 파일 또는 파일의 큰 섹션과 같이 동일한 큰 섹션을 식별하여 한 개의 사본만 저장하는 것입니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: This copy may be additionally compressed by single-file compression techniques.
answer: 이 사본은 단일 파일 압축 기술로 추가로 압축될 수 있습니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: For example a typical email system might contain 100 instances of the same one megabyte (MB) file attachment.
answer: 예를 들어 일반적인 이메일 시스템에는 동일한 1메가바이트(MB) 파일 첨부파일이 100개 있을 수 있습니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: Each time the email platform is backed up, all 100 instances of the attachment are saved, requiring 100 MB storage space.
answer: 이메일 플랫폼이 백업될 때마다 첨부파일의 100개 인스턴스가 모두 저장되므로 100MB의 저장 공간이 필요합니다.

question_EN: what is "data ingestion"
answer_EN: With data deduplication, only one instance of the attachment is actually stored; the subsequent instances are referenced back to the saved copy for deduplication ratio of roughly 100 to 1.
answer: 데이터 중복 제거 기능을 사용하면 첨부 파일의 인스턴스 하나만 실제로 저장되며, 이후 인스턴스는 저장된 사본을 다시 참조하여 약 100대 1의 중복 제거 비율로 저장됩니다.

question_EN: who balances the budget
answer_EN: A balanced budget (particularly that of a government) is a budget with revenues equal to expenditures , and neither a budget deficit nor a budget surplus ("the accounts balance").
answer: 균형 예산(특히 정부의 균형 예산)은 수입과 지출이 같고 예산 적자나 예산 흑자("계정 수지")가 없는 예산입니다.

question_EN: who balances the budget
answer_EN: More generally, it refers to a budget with no deficit, but possibly with a surplus.
answer: 보다 일반적으로는 적자는 없지만 흑자가 발생할 가능성이 있는 예산을 의미합니다.

question_EN: who balances the budget

answer: 순환 균형 예산은 매년 반드시 균형을 이루는 것이 아니라 경제 주기에 따라 균형을 이루는 예산으로, 호황기에는 흑자를 내고 불황기에는 적자를 내며 시간이 지나면서 상쇄되는 예산입니다.

question_EN: who balances the budget

question_EN: who balances the budget

question_EN: who balances the budget

answer: 대부분의 경제학자들도 균형 예산이 금리를 낮추고, 저축과 투자를 늘리고, 무역 적자를 줄이고, 경제가 장기간에 걸쳐 더 빠르게 성장하는 데 도움이 된다는 데 동의했습니다.

question_EN: what was fdr's new deal

question_EN: what is the si unit of pressure
answer_EN: Pressure as exerted by particle collisions inside a closed container.

question_EN: what is the si unit of pressure
answer_EN: Pressure (the symbol: p) is the ratio of force to the area over which that force is distributed.
answer: 압력(기호: p)은 힘이 분산되는 면적에 대한 힘의 비율입니다.

question_EN: what is the si unit of pressure

question_EN: what is the si unit of pressure

question_EN: what is the si unit of pressure

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about
answer_EN: She frequently mocks and dupes adults she encounters, an attitude likely to appeal to young readers; however, Pippi usually reserves her worst behavior for the most pompous and condescending of adults.

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about
answer_EN: After an initial rejection from Bonnier Publishers in 1944, Lindgren's manuscript was accepted for publication by the Swedish publisher Rabén and Sjögren .

question_EN: what is pippi longstocking about
answer_EN: The first three Pippi chapter books were published from 1945 to 1948, with an additional series of six books published in 1969–1975.

question_EN: what is in a tequila sunrise?

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: An embossed foil Notary Seal from the State of New York .
answer: 뉴욕 주에서 발행한 엠보싱 호일 공증인 인감 .

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: A notary public (or notary or public notary) in the common law world is a public officer constituted by law to serve the public in non-contentious matters usually concerned with estates, deeds, powers-of-attorney, and foreign and international business.
answer: 관습법 세계에서 공증인(또는 공증인 또는 공증인)은 일반적으로 재산, 증서, 위임장, 외국 및 국제 비즈니스와 관련된 비쟁송 사안에 대해 대중에게 서비스를 제공하기 위해 법에 의해 구성된 공직자입니다.

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: A notary's main functions are to administer oaths and affirmations, take affidavits and statutory declarations , witness and authenticate the execution of certain classes of documents, take acknowledgments of deeds and other conveyances, protest notes and bills of exchange, provide notice of foreign drafts, prepare marine or ship's protests in cases of damage, provide exemplifications and notarial copies, and perform certain other official acts depending on the jurisdiction .
answer: 공증인의 주요 기능은 선서 및 확인서 작성, 진술서 및 법정 신고서 작성, 특정 종류의 문서에 대한 증인 및 인증, 증서 및 기타 운송, 항의 메모 및 환어음에 대한 확인, 외국 어음의 통지, 해상 또는 선박의 손상 시 항의서 작성, 예증 및 공증 사본 제공, 기타 관할권에 따라 특정 공식 행위 수행입니다 .

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: Any such act is known as a notarization.
answer: 이러한 행위를 공증이라고 합니다.

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: The term notary public only refers to common-law notaries and should not be confused with civil-law notaries .
answer: 공증인이라는 용어는 관습법 공증인만을 의미하며 민법 공증인과 혼동해서는 안 됩니다.

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: With the exceptions of Louisiana , Puerto Rico , Quebec , whose private law is based on civil law , and British Columbia , whose notarial tradition stems from scrivener notary practice, a notary public in the rest of the United States and most of Canada has powers that are far more limited than those of civil-law or other common-law notaries, both of whom are qualified lawyers admitted to the bar: such notaries may be referred to as notaries-at-law or lawyer notaries.
answer: 루이지애나, 푸에르토리코, 민법을 기반으로 하는 퀘벡, 공증 전통이 서사 공증에서 비롯된 브리티시컬럼비아를 제외한 나머지 미국 및 캐나다 대부분의 주에서 공증인은 민법 공증인이나 변호사 자격이 있는 기타 일반법 공증인보다 훨씬 제한된 권한을 가지며, 이러한 공증인은 공증인 또는 변호사 공증인이라고 할 수 있습니다.

question_EN: what is the difference between notary public and commissioner of deeds
answer_EN: Therefore, at common law, notarial service is distinct from the practice of law , and giving legal advice and preparing legal instruments is forbidden to lay notaries such as those appointed throughout most of the United States of America.
answer: 따라서 관습법상 공증 서비스는 변호사 업무와 구별되며, 미국 대부분의 지역에서 공증인 등에게 법률 자문을 제공하고 법률 문서를 작성하는 것은 금지되어 있습니다.

question_EN: what is the function of the liver

question_EN: what is the function of the liver
answer_EN: It lies below the diaphragm in the abdominal-pelvic region of the abdomen.

answer: 간의 고도로 전문화된 조직은 작고 복잡한 분자의 합성과 분해를 포함한 다양한 대량의 생화학 반응을 조절하며, 이 중 다수는 정상적인 생명 기능에 필요합니다.

question_EN: what is the social norm approach?
answer_EN: While conducting research in the mid-1980s, two researchers, H.W. Perkins and A.D. Berkowitz , reported that students at a small U.S. college held exaggerated beliefs about the normal frequency and consumption habits of other students with regard to alcohol.

question_EN: what is the social norm approach?
answer_EN: These inflated perceptions have been found in many educational institutions, with varying populations and locations.

question_EN: what is the social norm approach?
answer_EN: Despite the fact that college drinking is at elevated levels, the perceived amount almost always exceeds actual behavior The social norms approach has shown signs of countering misperceptions, however research on resulting changes in behavior resulting from changed perceptions varies between mixed to conclusively nonexistent.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Packet switching is a digital networking communications method that groups all transmitted data – regardless of content, type, or structure – into suitably sized blocks, called packets .
answer: 패킷 스위칭은 콘텐츠, 유형 또는 구조에 관계없이 전송되는 모든 데이터를 패킷이라고 하는 적절한 크기의 블록으로 그룹화하는 디지털 네트워킹 통신 방식입니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: First proposed for military uses in the early 1960s and implemented on small networks in 1968, this method of data transmission became one of the fundamental networking technologies behind the Internet and most local area networks .
answer: 1960년대 초 군사용으로 처음 제안되어 1968년 소규모 네트워크에서 구현된 이 데이터 전송 방식은 인터넷과 대부분의 로컬 영역 네트워크의 기반이 되는 기본적인 네트워킹 기술 중 하나가 되었습니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Packet switching features delivery of variable-bit-rate data streams (sequences of packets) over a shared network.
answer: 패킷 스위칭은 공유 네트워크를 통해 가변 비트 전송률 데이터 스트림(패킷 시퀀스)을 전송하는 기능을 제공합니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: When traversing network adapters, switches, routers and other network nodes , packets are buffered and queued, resulting in variable delay and throughput depending on the traffic load in the network.
answer: 네트워크 어댑터, 스위치, 라우터 및 기타 네트워크 노드를 통과할 때 패킷이 버퍼링되고 대기열에 대기하므로 네트워크의 트래픽 부하에 따라 지연 및 처리량이 달라집니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Packet switching contrasts with another principal networking paradigm, circuit switching , a method which sets up a limited number of dedicated connections of constant bit rate and constant delay between nodes for exclusive use during the communication session.
answer: 패킷 스위칭은 또 다른 주요 네트워킹 패러다임인 회로 스위칭(통신 세션 동안 전용으로 사용하기 위해 노드 간에 일정한 비트 전송률과 일정한 지연으로 제한된 수의 전용 연결을 설정하는 방법)과 대조됩니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: In case of traffic fees (as opposed to flat rate), for example in cellular communication services, circuit switching is characterized by a fee per time unit of connection time, even when no data is transferred, while packet switching is characterized by a fee per unit of information.
answer: 정액제가 아닌 트래픽 요금의 경우, 예를 들어 셀룰러 통신 서비스에서 서킷 스위칭은 데이터가 전송되지 않더라도 연결 시간 단위당 요금이 부과되는 반면 패킷 스위칭은 정보 단위당 요금이 부과되는 특징이 있습니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Packet mode communication may be utilized with or without intermediate forwarding nodes (packet switches or routers ).
answer: 패킷 모드 통신은 중간 포워딩 노드(패킷 스위치 또는 라우터 )를 사용하거나 사용하지 않고도 사용할 수 있습니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: In all packet mode communication, network resources are managed by statistical multiplexing or dynamic bandwidth allocation in which a communication channel is effectively divided into an arbitrary number of logical variable-bit-rate channels or data streams.
answer: 모든 패킷 모드 통신에서 네트워크 리소스는 통신 채널을 임의의 수의 논리적 가변 비트 전송률 채널 또는 데이터 스트림으로 효과적으로 분할하는 통계적 다중화 또는 동적 대역폭 할당을 통해 관리됩니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Statistical multiplexing, packet switching and other store-and-forward buffering introduces varying latency and throughput in the transmission.
answer: 통계적 멀티플렉싱, 패킷 스위칭 및 기타 저장 후 전달 버퍼링은 전송에 다양한 지연 시간과 처리량을 유발합니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Each logical stream consists of a sequence of packets, which normally are forwarded by the multiplexers and intermediate network nodes asynchronously using first-in, first-out buffering.
answer: 각 논리적 스트림은 일련의 패킷으로 구성되며, 일반적으로 멀티플렉서와 중간 네트워크 노드에서 선입선출 버퍼링을 사용하여 비동기적으로 전달합니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: Alternatively, the packets may be forwarded according to some scheduling discipline for fair queuing , traffic shaping or for differentiated or guaranteed quality of service , such as weighted fair queuing or leaky bucket .
answer: 또는 패킷은 공정한 큐잉, 트래픽 쉐이핑 또는 가중 공정 큐잉 또는 누수 버킷과 같은 차별화되거나 보장된 서비스 품질을 위해 일부 스케줄링 규율에 따라 전달될 수 있습니다.

question_EN: When was packet switching technology develop?
answer_EN: In case of a shared physical medium, the packets may be delivered according to some packet-mode multiple access scheme.
answer: 공유 물리적 매체의 경우 패킷은 일부 패킷 모드 다중 액세스 체계에 따라 전달될 수 있습니다.

question_EN: who was president of texas when it was annexed into the united states?

question_EN: who was president of texas when it was annexed into the united states?

question_EN: What is the temperature of the star Altair

answer: 알테어는 적도에서의 속도가 약 286km/s로 빠르게 회전합니다.

question_EN: What is the temperature of the star Altair
answer_EN: A study with the Palomar Testbed Interferometer revealed that Altair is not spherical, but is flattened at the poles due to its high rate of rotation.
answer: 팔로마 테스트베드 간섭계를 사용한 연구 결과, 알테어는 구형이 아니라 높은 회전 속도로 인해 극이 평평하다는 사실이 밝혀졌습니다.

question_EN: What is the temperature of the star Altair
answer_EN: Other interferometric studies with multiple telescopes, operating in the infrared , have imaged and confirmed this phenomenon.
answer: 적외선에서 작동하는 여러 망원경을 사용한 다른 간섭계 연구에서도 이 현상을 이미지화하여 확인했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The Articles of Confederation : predecessor to the U.S. Constitution and drafted from Anti-Federalist principles
answer: 미국 연방 헌법: 미국의 전신 헌법 및 반연방주의 원칙에서 초안 작성

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Anti-Federalism refers to a movement that opposed the creation of a stronger U.S. federal government and which later opposed the ratification of the Constitution of 1787.
answer: 반연방주의는 더 강력한 미국 연방 정부의 설립에 반대하고 나중에 1787년 헌법의 비준에 반대했던 운동을 말합니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The previous constitution, called the Articles of Confederation , gave state governments more authority.
answer: 이전 헌법인 연방 헌법에서는 주 정부에 더 많은 권한을 부여했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Led by Patrick Henry of Virginia, Anti-Federalists worried, among other things, that the position of president, then a novelty, might evolve into a monarchy .
answer: 버지니아의 패트릭 헨리가 이끄는 반연방주의자들은 무엇보다도 당시 참신했던 대통령직이 군주제 로 발전할 수 있다고 우려했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: A book titled "The Anti-Federalist Papers " is a detailed explanation of American Anti-Federalist thought.
answer: "반연방주의자 논문"이라는 제목의 책에는 미국의 반연방주의 사상에 대한 자세한 설명이 나와 있습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: During the American Revolution and its immediate aftermath the term "federal" was applied to any person who supported the colonial union and the government formed under the Articles of Confederation .
answer: 미국 혁명과 그 직후에 "연방"이라는 용어는 식민지 연합과 연방 조약에 따라 형성된 정부를 지지하는 모든 사람에게 적용되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: After the war the group who felt that the national government under the Articles was too weak appropriated the name Federalist for themselves.
answer: 전쟁이 끝난 후, 헌법 조항에 따른 국가 정부가 너무 약하다고 생각한 그룹은 연방주의자라는 이름을 스스로 붙였습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Historian Jackson Turner Main wrote that, "to them, the man of 'federal principles' approved of 'federal measures,' which meant those that increased the weight and authority or extended the influence of the Confederation Congress."
answer: 역사학자 잭슨 터너 마인은 "그들에게 '연방 원칙'의 사람은 연방 의회의 비중과 권위를 높이거나 영향력을 확대하는 '연방 조치'를 승인했다"고 썼습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: As the Federalists moved to amend the Articles, eventually leading to the Constitutional Convention , they applied the term anti-federalist to their opposition.
answer: 연방주의자들이 헌법 개정을 추진하여 결국 제헌의회로 이어지면서 반대파에게 반연방주의자라는 용어를 적용했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The term implied, correctly or not, both opposition to Congress and unpatriotic motives.
answer: 이 용어는 정확하든 아니든 의회에 대한 반대와 비애국적인 동기를 모두 내포하고 있습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The Anti-Federalists rejected the term, arguing that they were the true Federalists.
answer: 반연방주의자들은 자신들이 진정한 연방주의자라고 주장하며 이 용어를 거부했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: In both their correspondence and their local groups they tried to capture the term.
answer: 서신과 현지 그룹 모두에서 이 용어를 포착하려고 노력했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: For example, an unknown anti-federalist signed his public correspondence as "A Federal Farmer" and the New York committee opposing the Constitution was called the "Federal Republican Committee."
answer: 예를 들어, 무명의 반연방주의자는 자신의 공개 서신에 "연방 농부"라고 서명했고, 헌법에 반대하는 뉴욕 위원회는 "연방 공화당 위원회"라고 불렀습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: However the Federalists carried the day and the name Anti-Federalist forever stuck.
answer: 그러나 연방주의자들은 그 날을 승리로 이끌었고 반연방주의자라는 이름은 영원히 고착화되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The Anti-Federalists were composed of diverse elements, including those opposed to the Constitution because they thought that a stronger government threatened the sovereignty and prestige of the states, localities, or individuals; those that claimed a new centralized, disguised "monarchic" power that would only replace the cast-off despotism of Great Britain with the proposed government; and those who simply feared that the new government threatened their personal liberties.
answer: 반연방주의자들은 더 강력한 정부가 주, 지방 또는 개인의 주권과 위신을 위협한다고 생각하여 헌법에 반대하는 사람들, 대영제국의 전제주의를 대체할 새로운 중앙집권적이고 위장된 '군주제' 권력을 주장한 사람들, 단순히 새 정부가 개인의 자유를 위협할 것을 두려워한 사람들 등 다양한 요소로 구성되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Some of the opposition believed that the central government under the Articles of Confederation was sufficient.
answer: 일부 반대파는 연방 조약에 따른 중앙 정부로 충분하다고 믿었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Still others believed that while the national government under the Articles was too weak, the national government under the Constitution would be too strong.
answer: 또 다른 사람들은 조약에 따른 국가 정부는 너무 약한 반면 헌법에 따른 국가 정부는 너무 강할 것이라고 믿었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Another complaint of the Anti-Federalists was that the Constitution provided for a centralized rather than Federal Government (and in the Federalist papers James Madison admits that the new Constitution has the characteristics of both a centralized and federal form of the government) and that a truly federal form of government was a leaguing of states as under the Articles of Confederation.
answer: 반연방주의자들의 또 다른 불만은 헌법이 연방정부가 아닌 중앙집권적 정부를 규정하고 있으며(제임스 매디슨은 연방주의자 논문에서 새 헌법이 중앙집권적 정부와 연방정부 형태의 특성을 모두 가지고 있다고 인정합니다), 진정한 연방정부 형태는 연방조항에 따른 주들의 연맹이라는 것이었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: During the period of debate over the ratification of the Constitution, numerous independent local speeches and articles were published all across the country.
answer: 헌법 비준을 둘러싼 논쟁의 기간 동안 전국 각지에서 수많은 독립적인 지역 연설과 기사가 발표되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Initially, many of the articles in opposition were written under pseudonyms, such as " Brutus ," " Centinel ," and " Federal Farmer ."
answer: 처음에 반대하는 글의 대부분은 "브루투스", "센티넬", "연방 농부"와 같은 가명으로 작성되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Eventually, famous revolutionary figures such as Patrick Henry came out publicly against the Constitution.
answer: 결국 패트릭 헨리와 같은 유명한 혁명가들이 공개적으로 헌법에 반대하는 목소리를 냈습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: They argued that the strong national government proposed by the Federalists was a threat to the rights of individuals and that the President would become a king.
answer: 그들은 연방주의자들이 제안한 강력한 중앙 정부가 개인의 권리를 위협하고 대통령이 왕이 될 것이라고 주장했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: They objected to the federal court system created by the proposed constitution.
answer: 그들은 제안된 헌법에 의해 만들어진 연방 법원 시스템에 반대했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: This produced a phenomenal body of political writing; the best and most influential of these articles and speeches were gathered by historians into a collection known as the Anti-Federalist Papers in allusion to the Federalist Papers .
answer: 이 글과 연설 중 가장 영향력 있는 글은 역사가들에 의해 '연방주의자 논문'을 암시하는 '반연방주의자 논문'으로 알려진 모음집으로 수집되었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: In every state the opposition to the Constitution was strong, and in two states — North Carolina and Rhode Island — it prevented ratification until the definite establishment of the new government practically forced their adherence.
answer: 모든 주에서 헌법에 대한 반대가 강했고, 노스캐롤라이나와 로드아일랜드 등 두 주에서는 새 정부가 확실하게 수립될 때까지 비준을 막아서 사실상 헌법 준수를 강요했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Individualism was the strongest element of opposition; the necessity, or at least the desirability, of a bill of rights was almost universally felt.
answer: 개인주의가 가장 강력한 반대 요소였으며, 권리장전의 필요성 또는 적어도 바람직함에 대해서는 거의 보편적으로 느끼고 있었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: In Rhode Island resistance against the Constitution was so strong that civil war almost broke out on July 4, 1788, when anti-federalist members of the Country Party led by Judge William West marched into Providence with over 1,000 armed protesters.
answer: 로드아일랜드에서는 헌법에 대한 저항이 너무 강해서 1788년 7월 4일 윌리엄 웨스트 판사가 이끄는 반연방주의자들이 1,000명이 넘는 무장 시위대를 이끌고 프로비던스로 진격하면서 내전이 발발할 뻔했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: The Anti-Federalists played upon these feelings in the ratification convention in Massachusetts .
answer: 반연방주의자들은 매사추세츠 주에서 열린 비준 대회에서 이러한 감정을 이용했습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: By this point, five of the states had ratified the Constitution with relative ease, but the Massachusetts convention was far more bitter and contentious.
answer: 이 시점까지 5개 주가 비교적 쉽게 헌법을 비준했지만 매사추세츠 주 대회는 훨씬 더 격렬하고 논쟁적이었습니다.

question_EN: Who Were the Anti Federalist
answer_EN: Finally, after long debate, a compromise (known as the " Massachusetts compromise ") was reached.
answer: 마침내 오랜 논쟁 끝에 '매사추세츠 타협'으로 알려진 타협안이 도출되었습니다.

question_EN: what was minimum wage in 2011
document_title_EN: Minimum wage in the United States
answer_EN: Minimum wage by U.S. state and U.S. territory ( American Samoa , Guam , Puerto Rico , Virgin Islands ), as of Jan. 1, 2013.
answer: 2013년 1월 1일 기준 미국 주 및 미국령(미국령 사모아 , 괌 , 푸에르토리코 , 버진 아일랜드)별 최저임금입니다.

question_EN: what was minimum wage in 2011
document_title_EN: Minimum wage in the United States
answer_EN: In the United States, workers are generally entitled to be paid no less than the statutory minimum wage .
answer: 미국에서는 일반적으로 근로자는 법정 최저 임금 이상을 받을 권리가 있습니다.

question_EN: what was minimum wage in 2011
document_title_EN: Minimum wage in the United States
answer_EN: The federal government mandates a nationwide minimum wage level of $7.25 per hour, while some states and municipalities have set minimum wage levels higher than the federal level, with the highest state minimum wage being $9.19 per hour in Washington as of 2013.
answer: 연방 정부는 전국적으로 시간당 7.25달러의 최저임금을 의무화하고 있지만, 일부 주와 지방 자치 단체에서는 연방 수준보다 높은 최저임금 수준을 설정하고 있으며, 2013년 기준 워싱턴 주에서 가장 높은 최저임금은 시간당 9.19달러입니다.

question_EN: what was minimum wage in 2011

question_EN: what is the purpose of child support?
answer_EN: In family law and public policy, child support (or child maintenance) is an ongoing, periodic payment made by a parent for the financial benefit of a child following the end of a marriage or other relationship.

question_EN: what is the purpose of child support?
answer_EN: Child maintenance is paid directly or indirectly by an obligor to an obligee for the care and support of children of a relationship that has been terminated, or in some cases never existed.

question_EN: what is the purpose of child support?

question_EN: what is the purpose of child support?

question_EN: what is atherosclerotic heart disease

question_EN: what is atherosclerotic heart disease

question_EN: what is atherosclerotic heart disease
answer_EN: Interestingly, chronically expanding lesions are often asymptomatic until lumen stenosis is so severe that blood supply to downstream tissue(s) is insufficient resulting in ischemia .

question_EN: what is the main component of vaccines
